// vader/vm/debug ŌĆö runtime debug/session context for the DAP debugger.
//
// A `DebugController` is threaded into `exec_entry` (and down to the host-op
// dispatcher) when a program runs under the step-debugger. It is `null` for
// every normal run / comptime evaluation / test, so those paths keep the VM's
// default behaviour and pay nothing.
//
// The record is deliberately data + callbacks (no `vader/dap` import) so the
// VM never depends on the DAP layer ŌĆö the closures that mutate DAP state live
// in `vader/dap` and are stored here by value. See the debugger plan
// (`.claude/plans/vscode-debugger-dap.md`) ┬¦4 for the anti-cycle rationale.

module "vader/vm"

/// Runtime debug/session context, passed to `exec_entry` when the program
/// runs under the DAP debugger ; `null` otherwise.
///
/// Phase 1 (proof of life) carries only `output_sink`. The DAP transport is
/// stdio, so program output must NOT reach fd 1 directly ŌĆö it would corrupt
/// the protocol stream ŌĆö so every `.IoWrite` host-op routes through the sink,
/// which the DAP server turns into `output` events. Phase 2 will extend this
/// record with breakpoints / step mode / an `on_pause` callback (plan ┬¦4),
/// which is why it is a struct rather than a bare sink function.
export DebugController :: struct {
    /// Program write hook. `stream` is `0` = stdout, `1` = stderr (matching the
    /// VM's `.IoWrite` Stream tag) ; `text` is the raw payload. Invoked in
    /// place of the direct `print` / `eprint` for every program write.
    output_sink: fn(i32, string) -> void
}
